<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-629-665  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 629 665.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  May 22 1989 n418 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM automates Ford factory; automated logistics and productionsystem emulates human actions.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>DePompa, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ford Motor Co and IBM's Systems Integration Division (DIS) developan automated manufacturing system for Ford's truck instrumentcluster plant in Saline, MI.andP;  Ford needed the system to beat theprice of competing vendors.andP;  Ford's Automated Logistics andProduction System (ALPS) is flexible and modular in design.andP;  Itemulates human senses such as touch, vision and artificialintelligence.andP;  It can manufacture anything that fits into a24-by-30-by-14-inch envelope.andP;  The on-line system consists of twotypes of robots, 10 robotic workstations in all, configured in twoassembly modules that perform some 40 assembly functions.andP;  Thesystem currently averages 4,600 to 4,700 units per day and bysummer 1989 should reach full capacity of 4,900, evenly dividedbetween simpler and more complex instrument panels.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ford Motor Co. (automation)International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    F.andO;Topic:     AutomationAutomobile IndustryComputer-Integrated ManufacturingRobotics IndustryModularity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Five focuses of automation at Ford's automated factory. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>